<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,778,919,945]" box="[189,778,919,945]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,919,945]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Description</emphasis>
(from 
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels" box="[415,770,919,945]" firstAuthor="De Laubenfels" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="1 - 140" refId="ref21918" refString="De Laubenfels M. W. 1932. The marine and fresh-water sponges of California. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 81 (2927): 1 - 140." type="journal article" year="1932">De Laubenfels 1932: 111–112</bibRefCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,966,1064]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
A thick plate-like mass (40 × 30 × 
<quantity box="[604,680,966,992]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
) encrusting stones in an intertidal cave. Color whitish in life and in alcohol. Surface smooth. Oscules of about 
<quantity box="[777,846,1002,1028]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
diameter are distributed evenly over the upper surface. Consistency firm to hard.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1105,1167]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">SKELETON. Dense, confused reticulation of thick oxeas. At the surface single spicules are arranged tangentially.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1207,1269]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<collectionCode box="[189,264,1207,1233]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">OXEAS</collectionCode>
(
<figureCitation box="[284,372,1207,1233]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,643,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,642,1852]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 18. Haliclona (Flagellia) edaphus (De Laubenfels, 1930) from California, SEM images of the spicules made from a fragment of the holotype (USNM 21444). A. Oxea. A 1. Detail of one of the apices. B–C. Flagellosigmas. B 1. Detail of long ending of flagellosigma. B 2. Detail of short ending of flagellosigma. D. Sigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836257/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
A–A1). Curved, cigar-shaped, sharply pointed, 272– 
<emphasis box="[1010,1054,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">314</emphasis>
–342 × 12– 
<emphasis box="[1196,1225,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">15</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1233,1248,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">8</emphasis>
–17 μm (De Laubenfels gives 260–270 × 15–16 μm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1309,1515]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
FLAGELLOSIGMAS (
<figureCitation box="[393,475,1309,1335]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,643,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,642,1852]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 18. Haliclona (Flagellia) edaphus (De Laubenfels, 1930) from California, SEM images of the spicules made from a fragment of the holotype (USNM 21444). A. Oxea. A 1. Detail of one of the apices. B–C. Flagellosigmas. B 1. Detail of long ending of flagellosigma. B 2. Detail of short ending of flagellosigma. D. Sigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836257/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
B–C). Elliptical in outline, with relatively large difference in length of long and short endings. Long endings with sharp curvature ending straight with a faint upturn in many spicules, short endings widely curved with only modest incurved apices. Length of long endings 76– 
<emphasis box="[1256,1285,1381,1407]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">89</emphasis>
–105 μm, short endings 64– 
<emphasis box="[400,429,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">67</emphasis>
–72 μm, width 53– 
<emphasis box="[658,687,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">66</emphasis>
–81 μm, thickness 1.5– 
<emphasis box="[965,980,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[987,1016,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">95</emphasis>
–3.5 μm. De Laubenfels did not differentiate flagellosigmas from normal sigmas, his drawing shows only a flagellosigma, sizes quoted by him were 30–100 μm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1556,1654]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
NORMAL SIGMAS (
<figureCitation box="[383,491,1556,1582]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="37.[189,232,1893,1919]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,643,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[189,1399,642,1852]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="Fig. 18. Haliclona (Flagellia) edaphus (De Laubenfels, 1930) from California, SEM images of the spicules made from a fragment of the holotype (USNM 21444). A. Oxea. A 1. Detail of one of the apices. B–C. Flagellosigmas. B 1. Detail of long ending of flagellosigma. B 2. Detail of short ending of flagellosigma. D. Sigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836257/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 18D</figureCitation>
). 
<collectingRegion box="[511,555,1556,1582]" country="Maldives" name="Uthuru" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Not</collectingRegion>
very common. Shape robust, symmetrical, apices sharply curved but not incurved, with many thin growth stages (not included in meaurements), 37– 
<emphasis box="[1095,1124,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">63</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1132,1147,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">9</emphasis>
–81 × 2.5– 
<emphasis box="[1276,1291,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">3</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1298,1313,1592,1618]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">3</emphasis>
–4 μm. De Laubenfels did not mention the presence of ‘normal’ sigmas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,497,1694,1720]" box="[189,497,1694,1720]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,497,1694,1720]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,497,1694,1720]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1398,1741,1839]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
California, near Carmel (Marine Ecoregion Northern California). Apparently confined to intertidal and shallow subtidal rocks. De Laubenfels mentions a second locality for this species, Point Fermin, near 
<collectingCountry box="[189,308,1813,1839]" name="Saint Pierre and Miquelon" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">San Pedro</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[324,464,1813,1839]" degrees="33.7054" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" precision="5" value="33.7054">33.7054° N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[476,633,1813,1839]" degrees="118.2938" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" precision="5" value="-118.2938">118.2938° W</geoCoordinate>
) (Marine Ecoregion Southern Californian Bight).
</paragraph>
