</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1399,1927,2025]" lastBlockId="37.[189,1399,266,468]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<bibRefCitation author="Lee" box="[189,368,1927,1953]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lee" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" refId="ref23382" refString="Lee W. L., Elvin D. W. &amp; Reiswig H. M. 2007. The Sponges of California. A Guide and Key to the Marine Sponges of California. Monterey Bay Sanctuary Foundation, Monterey." type="book" year="2007">
Lee 
<emphasis box="[241,301,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the 
<typeStatus box="[563,666,1927,1953]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">holotype</typeStatus>
(as 
<taxonomicName box="[716,968,1927,1953]" class="Demospongiae" family="Petrosiidae" genus="Xestospongia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edapha">
<emphasis box="[716,968,1927,1953]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Xestospongia edapha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and provided SEM evidence of the presence of both flagellosigmas and normal sigmas. They gave oxea sizes as 260- 
<emphasis box="[1153,1197,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">275</emphasis>
-300 × 12-13-15, flagellosigmas 75-(
<emphasis box="[418,487,1999,2025]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">87-96</emphasis>
)–118, and normal sigmas 46-(
<emphasis box="[858,926,1999,2025]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">52-81</emphasis>
)-118 μm. Except for the highest value of sigma length (which may be a misprint as it is the same as the upper size of the flagellosigmas), their data conform to the present description and are slightly different from De Laubenfels’ original description. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lee" box="[334,529,337,363]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lee" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refId="ref23382" refString="Lee W. L., Elvin D. W. &amp; Reiswig H. M. 2007. The Sponges of California. A Guide and Key to the Marine Sponges of California. Monterey Bay Sanctuary Foundation, Monterey." type="book" year="2007">
Lee 
<emphasis box="[385,444,337,363]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">et al.</emphasis>
(2007)
</bibRefCitation>
provided illustrations of the 
<typeStatus box="[869,972,337,363]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">holotype</typeStatus>
and of its skeleton. They treated the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Laubenfels" authorityYear="1930" box="[261,359,372,398]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus">
<emphasis box="[261,359,372,398]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">edaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as an adjective (by adjusting the combination with the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Laubenfels" authorityYear="1932" box="[1097,1255,373,398]" class="Demospongiae" family="Petrosiidae" genus="Xestospongia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1097,1255,373,398]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Xestospongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[1295,1381,372,398]" class="Demospongiae" family="Petrosiidae" genus="Xestospongia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edapha">
<emphasis box="[1295,1381,372,398]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">edapha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), but it is a noun from the Greek, meaning bottom or pavement. For that reason, the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Laubenfels" authorityYear="1930" box="[1235,1333,407,433]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus">
<emphasis box="[1235,1333,407,433]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">edaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its original spelling is retained here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,1398,508,569]" lastBlockId="38.[189,1399,266,439]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<bibRefCitation author="Dickinson" box="[189,404,508,534]" firstAuthor="Dickinson" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="1 - 55" refId="ref22353" refString="Dickinson M. G. 1945. Sponges of the Gulf of California. In: Allan Hancock Pacific Expediitions. First Series 11 (1): 1 - 55. Allan Hancock Foundation Publications of the University of Southern California, California. Available from http: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 5215603 [accessed 5 Sep. 2017]." type="book chapter" year="1945">Dickinson (1945)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species from the (Mexican) Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[1066,1185,508,534]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">California</collectingRegion>
(Carmen Island, approximately 
<geoCoordinate box="[369,482,543,569]" degrees="25.94" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" precision="555" value="25.94">25.94° N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[497,627,543,569]" degrees="111.09" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" precision="555" value="-111.09">111.09° W</geoCoordinate>
) at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[814,899,543,569]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="generic">
<quantity box="[814,895,543,569]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" unit="m" value="120.0">120 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
The oxeas of his specimen measured up to 400 × 18 μm and like De Laubenfels he did not differentiate flagellosigmas from normal sigmas, averaging them together as 40 μm. His pl. 15 fig. 29 shows a ‘distorted’ flagellosigma, which from the magnification provided has a long ending of about 60 μm long, with prominent long upturned curvature. Depth occurrence, larger oxeas and long upturned endings on the flagellosigmas together indicate a likely different species.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836257" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3836257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836257/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" startId="37.[189,232,1893,1919]" targetBox="[189,1399,643,1852]" targetPageId="37">
<paragraph blockId="37.[189,1399,1893,2024]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,285,1893,1919]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 18.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(De Laubenfels, 1930)" authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[296,944,1893,1919]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus" subGenus="Flagellia">
<emphasis box="[296,413,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Haliclona</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[434,542,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Flagellia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[563,661,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">edaphus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="De Laubenfels" box="[680,936,1893,1919]" firstAuthor="De Laubenfels" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="24 - 29" refId="ref21882" refString="De Laubenfels M. W. 1930. The sponges of California. Abstracts of dissertations for the degree of doctor of philosophy. Stanford University Bulletin 5 (98): 24 - 29." type="journal article" year="1930">De Laubenfels, 1930</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from California, SEM images of the spicules made from a fragment of the holotype (USNM 21444). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[985,1006,1928,1954]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A</emphasis>
. Oxea. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1106,1127,1928,1954]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1127,1136,1947,1961]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">1</emphasis>
. Detail of one of the apices. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[278,333,1963,1989]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">B–C</emphasis>
. Flagellosigmas. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[544,564,1963,1989]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">B</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[564,573,1982,1996]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">1</emphasis>
. Detail of long ending of flagellosigma. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1060,1080,1963,1989]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">B</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1079,1088,1982,1996]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">2</emphasis>
. Detail of short ending of flagellosigma. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[362,383,1998,2024]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">D</emphasis>
. Sigma.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="38.[189,1399,480,727]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Green &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bakus" box="[303,464,480,506]" firstAuthor="Bakus" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref21312" refString="Bakus G. D. &amp; Green K. D. 1994. The Porifera. In: Blake J. A. &amp; Lissner A. L. (eds) Taxonomic Atlas of the Benthic Fauna of the Santa Maria Basin and Western Santa Barbara Channel, Volume 2. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History, Santa Barbara." type="book" year="1994">Bakus (1994)</bibRefCitation>
reported two specimens, one from a depth of 
<quantity box="[1027,1133,480,506]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.85" metricValueMax="6.3" metricValueMin="5.4" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="58.5" valueMax="63.0" valueMin="54.0">54–63 m</quantity>
and one from 
<quantity box="[1314,1393,480,506]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
, collected from the Santa Maria Basin off the coast of Southern 
<collectingRegion box="[909,1032,517,543]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">California</collectingRegion>
. The descriptions are somewhat confused, and apparently the spicule measurements between the two specimens varied widely. Possibly, the specimen from 
<quantity box="[414,518,591,617]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.85" metricValueMax="6.3" metricValueMin="5.4" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="58.5" valueMax="63.0" valueMin="54.0">54–63 m</quantity>
could conform to 
<emphasis box="[734,755,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">H</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[769,919,591,617]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus" subGenus="Flagellia">
(
<emphasis box="[779,797,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">F</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[821,919,591,617]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">edaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the one from 
<quantity box="[1135,1209,591,617]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
deep appears to be different as the authors gave ‘sigma’ measurements of 13–250 μm, which are not compatible with the sizes from 
<emphasis box="[369,390,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">H</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="De Laubenfels" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[407,560,664,691]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Haliclona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus" subGenus="Flagellia">
(
<emphasis box="[417,435,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">F</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[462,560,664,690]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">edaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Assignment of these deep-water 
<collectingRegion box="[970,1089,664,690]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">California</collectingRegion>
records awaits proper redescription of the specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[189,1399,768,904]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<bibRefCitation author="Sim &amp; Kim's" box="[189,433,768,794]" firstAuthor="Sim" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="21 - 42" refId="ref24315" refString="Sim C. J. &amp; Kim M. H. 1988. A systematic study on the marine sponges in Korea. 7. Demospongiae and Hexactinellida. Korean Journal of Systematic Zoology 4 (1): 21 - 42." type="journal article" year="1988">Sim &amp; Kim’s (1988)</bibRefCitation>
record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Laubenfels" authorityYear="1930" box="[555,746,768,794]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chalinidae" genus="Gellius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="edaphus">
<emphasis box="[555,746,768,794]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Gellius edaphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<quantity box="[818,893,768,794]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="145.0">145 m</quantity>
depth off 
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1163,768,794]" name="South Korea" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">South Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[1180,1245,768,794]" degrees="33" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" precision="55555" value="33.0">33°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1258,1362,768,794]" degrees="127.5" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" precision="5555" value="127.5">127.5° E</geoCoordinate>
) is likewise uncertain, as the long ending of the pictured flagellosigma is smaller than 50 μm. Combined with the large geographic distance from the 
<typeStatus box="[721,772,842,868]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">type</typeStatus>
locality in California, this is sufficient indication of unlikely conspecificity.
</paragraph>
